bel": "Broad market absorption rate trend"}, {"id": "b_dom", "label": "Broad market DOM trend"}, {"id": "b_pend", "label": "Broad market pending count"}, {"id": "s_abs", "label": "Submarket absorption rate trend"}, {"id": "s_msp", "label": "Submarket median price trend"}, {"id": "s_pend", "label": "Submarket pending count"}, {"id": "covid", "label": "COVID pandemic disruption"}, {"id": "rate", "label": "Historic low rate environment"}, {"id": "walk", "label": "Walkable in-town remote work demand driver"}, {"id": "post", "label": "Post-effective-date recovery data (Oct-Dec 2020)"}, {"id": "irs", "label": "IRS closed-data-controls argument"}], "net_conclusion": "Market-Dependent as of September 22, 2020, with positive leading indicators in the submarket. Closed sale data reflects COVID disruption (lagging), but the pending count, rate environment, and submarket price resilience demonstrate the market had already turned. The IRS closed-data-controls argument ignores leading indicators and mischaracterizes conditions on the precise effective date. The estate''s Market-Dependent position is the more defensible conclusion.", "commentary": "Scenario 10 is the capstone estate scenario. Students must synthesize COVID-disrupted broad market data, a positively diverging submarket, competing IRS and estate positions, and both lagging and leading indicators. The critical skills: (1) correctly weighting pending sales as the most contemporaneously relevant indicator on the precise date; (2) identifying positive submarket divergence within a COVID-disrupted broad market; (3) articulating why the IRS closed-data argument ignores leading indicator evidence; and (4) producing a Form 706-quality narrative that withstands scrutiny from both a tax attorney and an IRS reviewer.", "classification_options": ["Improving", "Stable", "Declining", "Market-Dependent"], "min_rationale_chars": 20}'::jsonb,
  '{"factors": {"b_abs": {"present": true, "classification": "Declining", "rationale": "3.4 to 5.9 months in closed sale data - COVID demand disruption visible in lagging indicators. A real declining signal in the broad market."}, "b_dom": {"present": true, "classification": "Declining", "rationale": "28 to 39 days - COVID demand hesitation reflected in broad market closed data. Lagging but present."}, "b_pend": {"present": true, "classification": "Market-Dependent", "rationale": "94 pending vs. 89 active as of September 22, 2020 - a leading indicator showing demand had already returned. The broad market was recovering as of the effective date even if closed data had not yet reflected it."}, "s_abs": {"present": true, "classification": "Declining", "rationale": "3.8 to 6.1 months in submarket closed data - COVID disruption present in the submarket as well. A lagging signal."}, "s_msp": {"present": true, "classification": "Improving", "rationale": "+3.1% in the submarket - price resilience during COVID disruption. Submarket-specific positive divergence from the disrupted demand picture. An important moderating signal."}, "s_pend": {"present": true, "classification": "Improving", "rationale": "18 pending vs. 11 active in the submarket - an even stronger leading indicator than the broad market. Demand had returned robustly to this specific submarket as of September 22, 2020."}, "covid": {"present": true, "classification": "Declining", "rationale": "Documented proximate cause of closed sale deterioration - must be identified and explained. Operative as of September 22, 2020."}, "rate": {"present": true, "classification": "Improving", "rationale": "Sub-3.0% rates as of September 2020 - primary driver of the pending demand surge. Operative and documented as of the effective date."}, "walk": {"present": true, "classification": "Improving", "rationale": "Documented submarket-specific demand driver - buyers actively seeking walkable in-town properties during COVID. Explains submarket price resilience and stronger pending-to-active ratio relative to the broad market."}, "post": {"present": false, "rationale": "CRITICAL DISTRACTOR: The October-December 2020 closed sale boom is inadmissible as of September 22, 2020, however illustrative of what the leading indicators were already signaling."}, "irs": {"present": false, "rationale": "METHODOLOGICAL DISTRACTOR: Closed sale data is a lagging indicator and does not fully represent conditions as of September 22, 2020 when pending contracts substantially exceeded active supply and submarket prices were rising. The IRS argument ignores the most contemporaneously relevant evidence."}}}'::jsonb
